ints and St Olave, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Holbrook, Suffolk, England":"Holbrook, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Creeting St. Peter, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Creeting St Peter, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Almott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: ostensibly a topographic name from any of a large number of places called in Old English as ‘the old cottage’ (Old English <i>(e)ald</i> + <i>cot(e)</i>). In fact, however, it is generally an altered form of   Alcock  , in part at least for euphemistic reasons.","History: Louisa May Alcott (1832–88), author of <i>Little Women</i> (1869), was the daughter of Amos Bronson Alcott (1799–1888), who had changed the surname from <i>Alcox</i>. The family trace their descent from an Alcocke family who emigrated from England to MA with John Winthrop (see   Winthrop  ) in 1630."],"variants":[{"name":"Alcock","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Alcok</i>, a pet form of any of the many medieval personal names beginning with <i>Al-</i>, especially <i>Alan</i> and <i>Alexander</i>. The Middle English hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i> (see   Cocke  ) was very commonly added to personal names in Middle English: compare for example   Hancock   and   Wilcock  ."]},{"name":"Aucutt","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcott  ."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: Same as Catherine."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":21,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Katherine Almott was born in 1434, in Creeting St Mary with Creeting All Saints and St Olave, Suffolk, England, her father, Sir Thomas Almott II, was 20 and her mother, Lady Bridget Thorne, was 18. She married Sir John Clench III in 1455, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1475, in her hometown, at the age of 41, and was buried in Holbrook, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1434–1475":"1434–1475","1434–1500":"1434–1500","1433–1466":"1433–1466","1466–1516":"1466–1516","1414–1459":"1414–1459","1416–1434":"1416–1434","1459":"1459","1414":"1414","1434":"1434","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1433":"1433","1475":"1475","2 June 1459":"2. juuni 1459","1516":"1516","after 1466":"pärast 1466","1416":"1416","Creeting St Mary with Creeting All Saints and St Olave, Suffolk, England":"Creeting St Mary with Creeting All Saints and St Olave, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Holbrook, Suffolk, England":"Holbrook, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Creeting St. Peter, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Creeting St Peter, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1434–1475":"1434–1475","1434–1500":"1434–1500","1433–1466":"1433–1466","1466–1516":"1466–1516","1414–1459":"1414–1459","1416–1434":"1416–1434","1459":"1459","1414":"1414","1434":"1434","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1433":"1433","1475":"1475","2 June 1459":"2. kesäkuuta 1459","1516":"1516","after 1466":"1466 jälkeen","1416":"1416","Creeting St Mary with Creeting All Saints and St Olave, Suffolk, England":"Creeting St Mary with Creeting All Saints and St Olave, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Holbr